00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.500
Imagine you're trying to teach a robot
to tell the difference between a cat and a dog.

00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:09.000
Easy for you, right?
You've seen hundreds of cats and dogs.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:14.500
But how does a robot — who's never seen anything —
figure it out?

00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:20.000
That, my friend, is the whole challenge
of machine learning.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:26.000
And by the end of this video, you'll know
exactly how it works.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Machine learning is a type of artificial intelligence
where computers learn from examples

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
instead of being told exactly what to do
with step-by-step rules.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:57.000
In traditional programming,
a developer writes every rule.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:04.000
"If the animal has whiskers AND says meow,
it's a cat."

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:11.000
But machine learning flips that around.
You feed the computer thousands of labeled examples —

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
like pictures tagged "cat" or "dog" —
and it figures out the rules itself.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Pretty wild, right? Let's dig deeper.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
There are three main ways
a machine can learn.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:52.000
First: Supervised Learning.
This is like having a teacher.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:00.000
You give the computer data and the right answers.
The model learns by comparing its guesses to the correct labels.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Most of what you'll do in this course
uses supervised learning.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Second: Unsupervised Learning.
No labels this time!

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:19.000
The model looks for patterns on its own —
grouping similar things together.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:26.000
This is how streaming apps figure out
what kind of music you like without you telling them.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:32.000
Third: Reinforcement Learning.
Think of training a puppy.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:38.000
The model tries something, gets a reward if it does well,
gets nothing if it doesn't.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Over time, it learns to make better decisions.
This is how AI learns to play chess or video games.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Let's zoom in on supervised learning —
the most common type you'll encounter.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
It has four stages.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Stage 1: Collect Data.
Every AI model needs examples to learn from.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:24.000
If we want to recognize handwritten numbers,
we need thousands of images of digits —

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.000
written by real people,
in all sorts of handwriting styles.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:35.000
More data usually means a smarter model.
But the data also needs to be good.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:41.000
Stage 2: Label the Data.
Each example needs a tag — the correct answer.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:48.000
For images of animals, a human labels each one:
"cat," "dog," "rabbit."

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.000
This labeled dataset
is called training data.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Stage 3: Train the Model.
Now the magic happens.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:07.000
The model sees each labeled example and makes a guess.
Then it checks: was I right?

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:14.000
If not, it adjusts its internal settings —
called parameters — to do better next time.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:21.000
This process repeats thousands or even millions of times.
Each pass through the data is called an epoch.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Gradually, the model gets smarter.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Stage 4: Test the Model.
Finally, we show the model examples it's never seen before —

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:39.000
the test set. This tells us how well it actually learned,
not just memorized.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:45.000
If accuracy is high on the test set,
we have a solid model!

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:37.000
So what exactly is the model learning?
It's learning features —

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:42.000
characteristics that help distinguish
one thing from another.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:49.000
For a cat vs. dog classifier, features might include
ear shape, snout length, fur texture.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:57.000
The model doesn't know what a "snout" is —
but it learns that certain pixel patterns tend to appear in dogs.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Inside many modern AI models,
there's a structure called a neural network —

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:11.000
loosely inspired by the brain.
Information flows through layers of connections,

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:17.000
each layer finding more complex patterns.
The final layer recognizes objects.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:37.000
Sometimes a model gets too good at the training data —
it basically memorizes it instead of learning general rules.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:42.000
This is called overfitting.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:48.000
Think of a student who memorizes every practice problem
but can't solve a new one.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:55.000
The opposite problem is underfitting —
the model doesn't learn enough and does badly on everything.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:02.000
The goal: find the sweet spot.
A model that generalizes well to new data it's never seen.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:22.000
So here's the big picture:
Machine learning is about teaching computers through examples

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:27.000
instead of explicit rules.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:34.000
You collect and label data, train a model
by letting it guess and adjust,

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:40.000
then test it on new examples
to see how well it learned.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:47.000
That confused robot from the beginning?
With enough training data and the right model,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:53.000
it can now tell a cat from a dog
with 95% accuracy!

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Now it's your turn. Jump into the interactive training simulator
and train your own model.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:05.000
See you on the other side, ML Engineer.
